USA: Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It is funny with what schoolwork Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest, repeats in the Afghan issue the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself considered the dumbest.
When he finally dumped his eagerly awaited Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he wrote it over a copycat from Bush’s Iraqi script three years ago.
Not only did he use the word “as in Iraq” several times in the text itself, but he did not even hesitate to use the title of Bush’s January 2007 statement as the title of his own declaration: “A New Way Forward.”
Three years ago, he criticized Bush’s idea of sending fresh military reinforcements to Iraq, afflicted by the civil war, as an “irresponsible and, in its aftermath, catastrophic decision.”
The following months, however, showed that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of the field commanders, was the only possible and highly successful one so far that there is no mention of Iraq in the news reports today.
This did not improve Bush’s reputation, but objectively left his successor with a much more grateful starting point than could be expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will happen again.
He was once again asked by field commanders, notably the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation General Stanley McCristal, who even, despite his subordinate habit, harshly criticized the hesitant shooters in the White House.
He demanded 40,000 men to break the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but he did not think of anything better, so at least he cheated the general by 10,000 soldiers.
He was able to squeeze the promise of another 5,000 out of Europe, even though he originally counted at least 10.
The most problematic thing about Obama’s strategy seems to be his intention to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in as little as 18 months and to end this process within three years. The entire Obama doctrine raises more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that the half increase will yield the same fruit as the progress in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized, its leaders honor the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is characterised by the opposite sign - no one is to be trusted and no agreement is to be respected.
Under these conditions, Afghan security forces are ill-prepared, accustomed to changing masters every day according to how they feel.
Political institutions, even if they are formally established, will remain only a posthumous village, for which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to flourish.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily difficult given the opaqueness of the conditions, which further complicate Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Neither does the construction of a "capable state", which is the minimalist goal of the whole operation, seem too realistic.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy is astounded by his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is now on the brink of an explosion.
To believe that soldiers sent into a war turmoil in order to "quickly return home" will cause a miracle done here can only be a truly romantic soul, not touched by reality.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is pure irresponsibility, as the Taliban will perceive it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in combat operations in Afghanistan is declining.
European politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy relates to the war in the foothills of the Hindu Kush.
Another factor capable of radically intervening in the situation is the development of events around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions against Iran do not affect the United States, the question of whether to try to solve the problem by military force will be overwhelming.
It will be necessary to respond to it at the very moment when, according to Obama, America will move towards a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will also mean a dramatic turnaround in the Afghan situation.
The only patch for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left before the presidential election, and therefore there is still enough time to come up with another strategy if it turns out to be a total failure.
