Czech discovery: a substance that also affects the 'indicted' HIV viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that can slow the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the enhanced substance is that it also works on viruses that have already gained immunity against drugs.
This fact in some cases prevails over the fact that the compound on a common variant of the virus does not act as strongly as some already available drugs.
AIDS is not yet curable.
However, a mixture of drugs that prevent the multiplication of HIV in the body can significantly prolong the life of patients.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
In addition, incomplete suppression of the multiplication of the virus results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which drugs are already ineffective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, from V<0xC5><0xA0>CHT Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to cope with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metallocarbonates act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
