In recent studies, up to a third of those surveyed said they had experienced hallucinations at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. is 16 years old, lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends the gymnasium there.
Actually, a perfectly normal girl.
If it wasn't for the patterns and the voices.
During the breaks, she may be approached by a colophane with long, dark hair.
When she answers, her classmates look at her with surprise – no one but her sees and hears this boy.
This daring girl is considered a trapped dreamer, but Sarah K. doesn't, she knows.
He is awake, he hears and he sees the boy, just as he hears and he sees the girl sitting next to him in the bench.
He may even feel his presence, at least for a few moments.
It's a nice feeling, she likes that boy.
“Am I crazy?” he asks sometimes.
But he knows that this boy and other delusions are not real and will disappear again.
In the night the sights are rather depressing
Frequently, they are a burden.
When she sits in the classroom, she cannot watch the lesson many times, because the teacher in her eyes and ears is presenting a new classmate, but he explains it to everyone else in an audible and visible way on the mathematical equation board.
At night, the sights are rather depressing.
When she waits in her dark room for a sleep that comes rarely and too late, she often cannot tell whether she is awake or asleep, whether the images she sees, the grimaces, or the girl with bleeding cut wounds on her hands and feet arise behind her eyes, open or open.
Leave me alone, he's yelling at the characters.
She doesn't tell her parents and friends about it, they'd think she'd go crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She graduated last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Since she contacted psychologist Kasten on the Internet, she knows exactly that she hasn't gone mad.
Deception is also an art of despair.
If someone is socially isolated or is stripped of stimuli, they are more likely to have hallucinations, Kasten says.
I think the brain doesn't have enough work to do and it's taking care of its own fun.
Sarah K., the only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at 13 that the man she has been calling her dad since she thought he was her own father.
Because in visual and acoustic hallucinations the same brain regions are active, which also process real perceptions and sounds, it is difficult for those affected, like Sarah K., to distinguish between delusions and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "is taking place in the brain, there is also reality.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain produces, which is why they are so real.”
Also, night dreams are evaluated by Kasten as a form of hallucination.
The hallucination of healthy people is not fundamentally different from the hallucination in acute psychosis.
Compared to schizophrenics, mental health people are able to identify their delusions as unrealistic.
Kasten therefore advises its patients to evaluate hallucinations as an extraordinary ability.
The boundary between sleep and hallucination
In our world too focused on consciousness, the imaginary experience is unfortunately mostly pathologised, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and head physician of the Psychiatric and Psychotherapeutic Clinic of the Florence-Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
Psychosis is a difficult, painful disease, but it also brings positive, creativity - delusion is also the art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard investigated the so-called one-iroidal form of experience, a special form of altered consciousness to dream.
Oneiroid states are highly complex, detailed fictional dreams that the person in question considers to be real and cannot even distinguish them backwards from the waking state.
Oneiroid state of consciousness arises in extreme situations caused by trauma or disease, for example, patients with polyradicular inflammation who experience motor paralysis with full consciousness.
When a person is threatened by the loss of the world and of himself, perhaps permanent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own, imaginary world, which is disconnected from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A type of boundary state between sleep and hallucination.
Because in reality it is not possible to manage a situation, there will be a change of worlds, but the real situation becomes an idea.
An intense form of support of the senses and the transfer of the senses in some unbearable situation, which allows us to people's own ability to form, to pass in a moment to loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in the memory
Also art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen describes his one-iroid experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" (Exchange of the Heart) as a rescue action of the soul.
He was 49 years old when, after a heart valve surgery followed by a heart transplant, his consciousness embarked on a several-day journey while his body lay motionless in an intensive care unit.
Claussen immersed himself in the world he created, visited foreign times and places: he becomes an old man clinging to bed, in a train sanatorium, the robot takes care of his health.
She lives in the early Middle Ages among the nobility that produces narcotic substances from the blood.
On a motorbike, he is taken by a Greek to his homeland, surfs on a hospital bed in the Alps and meets a Korean mobster.
It immerses itself completely in the imaginary story, everything is real, even later in the memories.
For Claussen, these inner paths are fundamentally different from any dream.
A dream is a different state, it describes its experience.
In contrast to dreams, the memories of those mental journeys are clearly clear even after years and in insignificant details.
Even brighter and more intense than the real experience.
The intensity of this experience breaks the horizon of our other true experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
After all, oneiroid states, psychoses, hallucinations and drug addictions show how fragile our inner images of external reality are, even in a waking state.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
A fact that can also be enriching.
