75% of working mothers have work-related maternity problems.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially among younger-age women who intend to have a child.
This is the result of the study 'Fertility and working careers of Spanish women', conducted by the CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The study involved 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75, and the results are unambiguous: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities in the labour market due to maternity.
The study highlights that at the beginning of the partnership there are many differences in opinions about the number of children depending on whether they work or not, and also according to the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have a stable job, start living with their partner earlier, give birth to the first child earlier, and overall have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, postpone cohabitation and motherhood, and have fewer descendants.
"Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with stable employment have their first child, on average, 3.7 years from the beginning of cohabitation, a figure of 4.1 for women who have devoted most of their lives to achieving stable employment and have therefore had to postpone cohabitation and the arrival of children.
The type of profession also has a strong impact on maternity, although it has a smaller impact on the start time of cohabitation with the partner,” explains Margarita Delgado, who is a researcher at CSIC.
Another factor affecting the age of women at the time of the marriage of the anaroid offspring is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the level of education, the older women get married and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the age group of 35 to 49, women with primary and higher education gave birth to their first child at 25.1 and 32.1 respectively.
"There is still another difference between women depending on their degree of education.
Women with basic education get married and give birth to their first child before they can find a stable job, while women with secondary or higher education do the opposite, preferring to get a stable job, before getting married and giving birth to their first child,” said Delgado.
