The manual brake auxiliary system is already a compulsory equipment.
As in the case of ABS anti-lock system, it will also be with ESP stability control, with manual brake auxiliary systems, all this will become a mandatory equipment of European cars.
In fact, it is already part of the mandatory equipment of all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the others a deadline is set to remove the shortage, which is February 2011.
The measure introduced in the EU aims to increase the protection of pedestrians, while working in a way that can help prevent many collisions.
The auxiliary handbrake system increases the brake pressure in an emergency, which the system detects after the driver steps down.
But it is not always possible to maintain this pressure until the end.
According to a study by the automotive parts manufacturer Bosch, one-third of drivers who have an accident did not brake before crashing, and half of them did not fully use the brake power.
Up to 1,100 accidents
Conversely, this assistance requires the maximum of the braking system, shortening the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study conducted in the EU itself, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of equipment, up to 1,100 pedestrian-related fatalities could be prevented annually.
Reducing this number will be even more significant-according to calculations would prevent one of four accidents with an impact on people-after the introduction of the so-called intelligent handbrake systems.
In this case, the vehicles will be equipped with a system that (using radar or camera) detects obstacles and reports them to the driver, except for light braking.
